<sec id="id-b294dbe6-0e88-463c-b75c-2c5fd10cd13b"><title><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="e36af5db-b92a-417a-c32f-96f32d8e3750" timestamp="1627508496857"?>Fundamental components of a learning transaction<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="e36af5db-b92a-417a-c32f-96f32d8e3750"?></title><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="e3e19122-fa38-4023-830d-9c0f422ffef1" timestamp="1627521510344"?>Learning transactions can be modelled for registering, reference and re-use as scenarios and scenario components. Business semantic descriptive techniques can used to identify and specify the key components of a learning transaction, i.e., as learning objects (or LET objects).<xref ref-type="fn" as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-ce37473a-a901-49f0-c205-f35a0194daa7" id="id-6235f851-075c-411e-8b2c-f84ed11dce0b" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><fn id="id-ce37473a-a901-49f0-c205-f35a0194daa7"><p>The rules in this classes of ISO/IEC 15944-1 apply here to Annex B also. They have been adapted in a LET context.</p></fn> The Learning Transaction Model (LTM) has three required components namely "Person", "Process", and "Data. These three fundamental components are presented graphically in <xref as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-288b7316-86d8-4b0e-97c6-4e504b59b9fc" ref-type="fig" id="id-00ab9485-8af1-4ff5-e686-a4ac96414fd5" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref>.<xref ref-type="fn" as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-e4da8e0b-dcfa-49c2-f643-a62d924eb22c" id="id-13fb4245-43ea-45f8-8caf-cc7c1de1ef2d" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><fn id="id-e4da8e0b-dcfa-49c2-f643-a62d924eb22c"><p>In ISO/IEC 15944-1 for these three fundamental elements, are the essential BOV aspects of the learning transaction model, along with associated rules, definitions and terms as well as other attributes are stated in the following clauses:</p><p>(1) Clause 6.2 "Rules governing the Person Component" (and further Annex );</p><p>(2) Clause 6.3 "<italic>Rules governing the Process Component"</italic> (and further Annex F); and,</p><p>(3) Clause 6.4 <italic>"Rules governing the Data Component"</italic> (and further Annex G).</p><p>[3]) Most of the existing ISO/IEC JTC1 standards as well as many of the existing ISO, IEC or ITU standards (including those referenced in <xref as:rid="chunks/82851/id-b87c781c-4bc2-4d7c-88ef-b0f473222b35.xml#id-b87c781c-4bc2-4d7c-88ef-b0f473222b35" ref-type="sec" id="id-cc996773-104a-4041-8264-cf3c90a27306" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref>above) do not or were not designed to be able to address any two or more of the “Person”, data and/or process components in an integrated manner.</p><p><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the footnote"?></p></fn> This is because both a business transaction and a learning transaction are sub-types of an agreed upon commitment exchange among autonomous parties.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="e3e19122-fa38-4023-830d-9c0f422ffef1"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="64ecc5ef-8439-407e-acc3-49a81ca30f29" timestamp="1627508525637"?><bold>Rule B-001:</bold><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="64ecc5ef-8439-407e-acc3-49a81ca30f29"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="95c5f11f-0de7-4f7a-bbc9-a13ea5e9b7cf" timestamp="1627508525637"?><bold>Any learning transaction has three fundamental components</bold><sup>[3])</sup> <bold>namely: (1) a “Person” (as a whole or per its three sub-types, i.e., of individual, organization, or public administration) as party(ies) to any commitment exchange including that of the nature of a learning transaction.</bold><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="95c5f11f-0de7-4f7a-bbc9-a13ea5e9b7cf"?></p><fig id="id-288b7316-86d8-4b0e-97c6-4e504b59b9fc" specific-use="size:M"><caption><title><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="b8b723de-78e9-43c3-a8e0-8242b456fd80" timestamp="1627520786434"?>Learning Transaction Model – Fundamental components<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="b8b723de-78e9-43c3-a8e0-8242b456fd80"?></title></caption><graphic xlink:href="images/82851/B1" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/></fig><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="3cffc0a0-81fe-423b-d196-de1e49451141" timestamp="1627521434764"?>Using UML as a Formal Description Technique yields the following UML-based representation of the Learning Transaction Model and is presented as <xref as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-f209153e-a414-4d80-d241-17baa3bf4b84" ref-type="fig" id="id-1aa57a5c-b83e-43fb-e01e-23a4c80e7f83" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="3cffc0a0-81fe-423b-d196-de1e49451141"?><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="7671038" change-id="6ebd534b-bb46-43f7-b36b-e182979a22d6" text="This UML-based representation incorporates the rules governing the interworking of these three fundamental components as specified in ISO/IEC 15944-1." timestamp="1644576146527"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="4616534e-5f35-4c92-8395-023e48aef80f" timestamp="1627521434764"?><xref ref-type="fn" as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-0097ac34-10b9-4d45-c32e-85337c412f98" id="id-3060e45c-bb91-4e7c-befd-668766f74a7f" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><fn id="id-0097ac34-10b9-4d45-c32e-85337c412f98"><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="4616534e-5f35-4c92-8395-023e48aef80f"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="7671038" change-id="b6af6668-8123-48a2-caf2-83cfc348a44d" timestamp="1644576151211"?>This UML-based representation incorporates the rules governing the interworking of these three fundamental components as specified in ISO/IEC 15944-1.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="b6af6668-8123-48a2-caf2-83cfc348a44d"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="ffe4e9cf-d9f9-478c-9a3f-c3e562516934" timestamp="1627521434764"?></p></fn><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="ffe4e9cf-d9f9-478c-9a3f-c3e562516934"?></p><fig id="id-f209153e-a414-4d80-d241-17baa3bf4b84" specific-use="size:M"><caption><title><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="4a869d66-04e0-4ed2-9e88-cbe3faf53036" timestamp="1627521442670"?>UML-based Representation of <xref as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-288b7316-86d8-4b0e-97c6-4e504b59b9fc" ref-type="fig" id="id-32417a89-5b99-4d32-a3b7-3b26412d5503" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref>– Learning Transaction Model<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="4a869d66-04e0-4ed2-9e88-cbe3faf53036"?></title></caption><graphic xlink:href="images/82851/B2" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/></fig><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="4347b684-0918-4748-c048-da4418c75e2a" timestamp="1627521211364"?>The learning transaction model (LTM) focuses on and addresses the essential needs of commitment exchange among autonomous parties, i.e., the ability of Persons as parties to a learning transaction being able to make commitments and to do so while maximizing the use of automated methods. This is in addition to existing standards which pertain to various aspects of information exchange only.<xref ref-type="fn" as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-9ce3aa92-e873-47ca-9193-489ba992696b" id="id-eb19bde1-3898-4bcc-e24b-7baa4ffc5b7c" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><fn id="id-9ce3aa92-e873-47ca-9193-489ba992696b"><p>It is important that users of this part of ISO/IEC 15944 familiarize themselves with Part 1, Clause 6.3.1 titled <italic>"Learning transactions commitment exchange added to information exchange</italic>" including the rules and definitions/terms, i.e., "Person", and "commitment" as well as its normative text.</p></fn> As such, what sets Open-edi apart from information exchange in general are six (6) characteristics.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="4347b684-0918-4748-c048-da4418c75e2a"?><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="7671038" change-id="c86755c5-841b-47b9-9675-05d5987e03ee" text="See further in ISO/IEC 15944-1 Clause 5 \"Characteristics of Open-edi\", where of these six (6) characteristics are described in more detail." timestamp="1644576189196"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="fbdeffb5-dd79-4447-a2c9-700f20beaaea" timestamp="1627521211364"?><xref ref-type="fn" as:rid="chunks/82851/id-8a5f0397-d536-4795-8bf9-26e46db7e83f.xml#id-63c7ca2f-3939-4ada-d0dd-6c9552cb5d78" id="id-f0a06876-f556-4c3c-bc1e-6e47f29d7155" xmlns:as="http://niso-sts-authoring-solution/authoring-schema"><?fontoxml-text-placeholder text="type the link text"?></xref><fn id="id-63c7ca2f-3939-4ada-d0dd-6c9552cb5d78"><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="fbdeffb5-dd79-4447-a2c9-700f20beaaea"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="7671038" change-id="bad17a9d-0e16-4b62-8f4c-73934c102d7f" timestamp="1644576194899"?>See further in ISO/IEC 15944-1 Clause 5 "<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="bad17a9d-0e16-4b62-8f4c-73934c102d7f"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="62321405-1c1f-4853-c49e-157a36e92933" timestamp="1627521211364"?><italic><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="62321405-1c1f-4853-c49e-157a36e92933"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="7671038" change-id="220f5c9d-3220-4b5c-fb09-deef0f9414f4" timestamp="1644576194899"?>Characteristics of Open-edi",<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="220f5c9d-3220-4b5c-fb09-deef0f9414f4"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="c23e1742-2c75-4c68-f9ee-e22ce154b516" timestamp="1627521211364"?></italic><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="c23e1742-2c75-4c68-f9ee-e22ce154b516"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="7671038" change-id="ff6050c0-1555-4e33-ed8b-25b9f5606c6f" timestamp="1644576194899"?> where of these six (6) characteristics are described in more detail.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="ff6050c0-1555-4e33-ed8b-25b9f5606c6f"?><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="808082ac-68ed-4fe5-b11a-cf186a14419a" timestamp="1627521211364"?></p></fn><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="808082ac-68ed-4fe5-b11a-cf186a14419a"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="132a7a93-f2bc-41df-ff86-5302c3cabfdb" timestamp="1627508525636"?>They are:<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="132a7a93-f2bc-41df-ff86-5302c3cabfdb"?></p><list list-type="dash"><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="5b457335-a098-42ef-d26b-5ed5dd0ca231" timestamp="1627508525636"?><list-item id="id-829e8b75-4bb4-4ddd-d38c-63fefba3e7cb"><p>actions based upon following clear, predefined rules;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-a05a2dfc-cf74-406b-cd6d-56bb09b192c4"><p>commitments of the parties involved;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-37fc2900-cb9b-485b-d97f-bfad052eb3ce"><p>commitments among the parties are automated;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-9156ff38-dfaa-4897-eec0-7172659daa72"><p>parties control and maintain their states;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-7825c718-345e-49eb-ee97-86d8c0326176"><p>parties act autonomously; and,</p></list-item><list-item id="id-cb0de404-c8f9-495d-c715-7e2a87e53c8b"><p>multiple simultaneous transactions can be supported.</p></list-item><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="5b457335-a098-42ef-d26b-5ed5dd0ca231"?></list><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="bab8e36a-6b45-4c59-f9fe-bb97d8e5cfc2" timestamp="1627508525636"?>Electronic learning transactions therefore require:<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="bab8e36a-6b45-4c59-f9fe-bb97d8e5cfc2"?></p><list list-type="order"><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="e9ea7915-cefa-493f-c3f6-20abd360e8e5" timestamp="1627508525636"?><list-item id="id-97198694-c99a-4975-9f56-93f9891eecf2"><p>a clearly understood purpose, mutually agreed upon goal(s) explicitness and unambiguity;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-9ad44093-e910-4ebd-ca71-c60aa02d2ea8"><p>pre-definable set(s) of activities and/or processes, pre-definable and structured data;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-daa7a081-6e3f-4f93-c178-5b99912968a2"><p>commitments among Persons being established through electronic data interchange;</p></list-item><list-item id="id-9c44516a-3ad6-495a-e8bd-e1b9c4b24cf5"><p>computational integrity and related characteristics; and,</p></list-item><list-item id="id-65769591-1ebe-4568-fab7-839152e81e18"><p>the above being specifiable through Open-edi Description Technique(s) (OeDTs) (as the use of a Formal Description Technique(s) in support of modelling e-business), and executable through information technology systems for use in real world actualizations.</p></list-item><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="e9ea7915-cefa-493f-c3f6-20abd360e8e5"?></list><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="ab2fa1ff-2c21-41ec-848a-0960b7906633" timestamp="1627508525635"?>These and related requirements of electronic learning transactions are specified in the form of "constraints".<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="ab2fa1ff-2c21-41ec-848a-0960b7906633"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="bbe375e1-22f0-459e-eb46-ab5395e8ece6" timestamp="1627508525635"?>The concept of "constraint" has already been defined in ISO standards. The existing ISO definition has been adapted in a LET context as follows:<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="bbe375e1-22f0-459e-eb46-ab5395e8ece6"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="d274c3a8-b85c-482b-cf4f-7f5a06819c4f" timestamp="1627508525635"?><bold><italic>constraint (in LET privacy protection)</italic></bold><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="d274c3a8-b85c-482b-cf4f-7f5a06819c4f"?></p><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="93d7a449-2847-4bcd-f1bd-6ba947e8aa50" timestamp="1627508525635"?><bold>rule</bold>, explicitly stated, that prescribes, limits, governs or specifies any aspect of a <bold>learning transaction</bold><?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="93d7a449-2847-4bcd-f1bd-6ba947e8aa50"?></p><non-normative-note><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="fb107dc3-e148-4b83-f9d6-b02ebed5fc2c" timestamp="1627776691493"?>Constraints are specified as rules forming part of components of Open-edi scenarios, i.e., as scenario attributes, roles, and/or sets of recorded information (SRIs).<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="fb107dc3-e148-4b83-f9d6-b02ebed5fc2c"?></p></non-normative-note><non-normative-note><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="a25ee39a-1355-41f2-b78f-6ff6a48a72fe" timestamp="1627776699361"?>For constraints to be registered for implementation in Open-edi, they must have unique and unambiguous identifiers.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="a25ee39a-1355-41f2-b78f-6ff6a48a72fe"?></p></non-normative-note><non-normative-note><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="1e10ee12-decb-4b6b-bf8a-6bb83b65cd9f" timestamp="1627776711871"?>A constraint may be agreed to among parties (condition of contract) and is therefore considered an "internal constraint". Or a constraint may be imposed on parties, (e.g., laws, regulations, etc.), and is therefore considered an "external constraint".<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="1e10ee12-decb-4b6b-bf8a-6bb83b65cd9f"?></p></non-normative-note><non-normative-note><p><?fontoxml-change-addition-start author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="ee783402-f4a6-4b7b-cbca-ea50d00031dd" timestamp="1627776725448"?>Adapted from ISO/IEC 15944-1.<?fontoxml-change-addition-end change-id="ee783402-f4a6-4b7b-cbca-ea50d00031dd"?></p></non-normative-note><?fontoxml-change-deletion author-id="andres@nii.ac.jp" change-id="0506cd0b-bdb1-483d-e4eb-867b6033a295" text="[4]) This UML-based representation incorporates the rules governing the interworking of these three fundamental components as specified in ISO/IEC 15944-1.[3]) Most of the existing ISO/IEC JTC1 standards as well as many of the existing ISO, IEC or ITU standards (including those referenced in Clause 2 above) do not or were not designed to be able to address any two or more of the “Person”, data and/or process components in an integrated manner.(3) Clause 6.4 \"Rules governing the Data Component\" (and further Annex G).(2) Clause 6.3 \"Rules governing the Process Component\" (and further Annex F); and,(1) Clause 6.2 \"Rules governing the Person Component\" (and further Annex E);" timestamp="1627520871264"?><p/></sec>
